{"pk": 9, "path": "0001000100030003", "depth": 4, "numchild": 0, "translation_key": "ea817511-2c73-4271-98d4-a57a17a44431", "locale": 1, "title": "ANNUAL GENERAL MEETING REPORT", "draft_title": "ANNUAL GENERAL MEETING REPORT", "slug": "annual-general-meeting-report", "content_type": 55, "live": true, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/home/news/annual-general-meeting-report/", "owner": 1, "seo_title": "", "show_in_menus": false, "search_description": "", "go_live_at": null, "expire_at": null, "expired": false, "locked": false, "locked_at": null, "locked_by": null, "first_published_at": null, "last_published_at": null, "latest_revision_created_at": null, "live_revision": null, "alias_of": null, "date": "2021-02-03", "intro": "ANNUAL GENERAL MEETING REPORT", "body": "

Ards held its AGM via Zoom on Monday night, 1st February.

The dominant feature of the reports and discussions was the uncertainty and difficulties caused by Covid-19 and the on-off Government restrictions since March. These prevented the club from carrying out its usual fund-raising and other activities, and compressed the playing season to 7 weekends, beginning in mid-July. Importantly also, it necessitated the postponement of the 75th anniversary dinner in September, though it is hoped to hold this in April.

The Chairman thanked the club\u2019s office holders for their commitment over the year, especially those who had worked on the ground and helped put in place the essential Covid health and safety procedures to enable practices and matches to be played, although the pavilion at Londonderry Park remained closed. It was not possible, however, to have any junior cricket, including the annual Primary School Kwik Cricket tournament.

Both senior teams played in small, regional leagues. The 1sts came up against strong Bangor and Holywood sides, both relegated from Section 1 in 2019. They were well beaten in these games but shared the honours against Donaghadee.

Sam Ingham retained the batting cup; the bowling trophy went to Andrew Savage

The 2nds\u2019 league also comprised teams of mixed standard and while they didn\u2019t register a win, the matches were all played in great spirit and provided a good standard of cricket for the young team, which augurs well for hopefully resuming playing against opposition of a similar standard this Summer.

The batting and bowling awards were both shared: the former by Ross McCaughey and Dominic Allen; the latter by Eddie Hawkins and Rory McVeigh.

The Officers of the Club elected at the meeting were: Les Jones, Chairman; Roy Keenan, Honorary Secretary; David McCullough, Honorary Treasurer. Andrew Savage and Conn Crawford will again captain the 1sts and 2nds respectively. Stanley Woods and Co. continue their long association with the club as its auditors.

Caught:
If a fielder catches the ball on the full after the batsman has hit it with his bat. However, if the fielder catches the ball, but either during the catch or immediately afterwards touches or steps over the boundary, then the batsman scores six runs and is not out.

fields.body: As of 2021, we have developed a new website which aims to provide an all new look and feel that can create the best platform for all those involved with the club to flourish and become all round better at the game of cricket.

Last season's performance awards are:
1sts' Batting - Sam Ingham
1sts' Bowling - Andrew Savage
2nds' Batting - Eddie Hawkins and Rory McVeigh (shared)
2nds' Bowling - Ross McCaughey and Dominic Allen (shared)
Highest Score - Sam Ingham, 87* against Donaghadee on 8th August
Best Bowling - Ross McCaughey - 3 for 24 against Dundrum 2nds on 16th August
Young Player of the Year - Ross McCaughey

Ards held its AGM via Zoom on Monday night, 1st February.
The dominant feature of the reports and discussions was the uncertainty and difficulties caused by Covid-19 and the on-off Government restrictions since March. These prevented the club from carrying out its usual fund-raising and other activities, and compressed the playing season to 7 weekends, beginning in mid-July. Importantly also, it necessitated the postponement of the 75th anniversary dinner in September, though it is hoped to hold this in April.
The Chairman thanked the clubs office holders for their commitment over the year, especially those who had worked on the ground and helped put in place the essential Covid health and safety procedures to enable practices and matches to be played, although the pavilion at Londonderry Park remained closed. It was not possible, however, to have any junior cricket, including the annual Primary School Kwik Cricket tournament.
Both senior teams played in small, regional leagues. The 1sts came up against strong Bangor and Holywood sides, both relegated from Section 1 in 2019. They were well beaten in these games but shared the honours against Donaghadee.
Sam Ingham retained the batting cup; the bowling trophy went to Andrew Savage
The 2nds league also comprised teams of mixed standard and while they didnt register a win, the matches were all played in great spirit and provided a good standard of cricket for the young team, which augurs well for hopefully resuming playing against opposition of a similar standard this Summer.
The batting and bowling awards were both shared: the former by Ross McCaughey and Dominic Allen; the latter by Eddie Hawkins and Rory McVeigh.
The Officers of the Club elected at the meeting were: Les Jones, Chairman; Roy Keenan, Honorary Secretary; David McCullough, Honorary Treasurer. Andrew Savage and Conn Crawford will again captain the 1sts and 2nds respectively. Stanley Woods and Co. continue their long association with the club as its auditors.
Ards Cricket Club wishes all its players, sponsors and followers a safe, healthy and less uncertain 2021.

The Annual General Meeting, postponed from Monday 26th October 2020 in ongoing Covid-19 restrictions, will be held via Zoom on Monday 1st February at 7.30pm.
If you wish to attend, please email Roy Keenan (roy.keenan@btopenworld.com) by Friday 28th January and the link will be sent to join the meeting.

The attached, slightly damaged, the photograph has been provided by Michael Loane (3rd on left, back row). The others are:

Back Row

Mohammed Javed, Richard Fitzsimmons, Richard Warnock, Alfie Wright, Seamus Rice, Mark Graham, Paul Davidson, and Geddis Dunn

Front Row

Jonathan Montgomery, Rab Dunn, Derek Lorimer, Archie Moore and Billy Doherty

If the non-striker leaves his crease (in preparation to run) while the bowler is running up, the bowler may run him out without bowling the ball. Batsmen cannot be run out while the ball is dead - so they may confer in the middle of the pitch between deliveries if they desire.

Hit Wicket:
If, in attempting to hit a ball or taking off for a first run, the batsman touches and breaks the wicket. This includes with the bat or dislodged pieces of the batsman's equipment - even a helmet or spectacles!

Handle The Ball:
If a batsman touches the ball with a hand not currently holding the bat, without the permission of the fielding side. This does not include being hit on the hand by a delivery, or any other non-deliberate action.

Obstructing The Field:
If a batsman deliberately interferes with the efforts of fielders to gather the ball or effect a run out. This does not include running a path between the fielder and the wicket so that the fielder cannot throw the stumps down with the ball, which is quite legal, but does include any deliberate attempt to swat the ball away.

Hit The Ball Twice:
If a batsman hits a delivery with his bat and then deliberately hits the ball again for any reason other than to defend his wicket from being broken by the ball. If the ball is bouncing or rolling around near the stumps, the batsman is entitled to knock it away so as to avoid being bowled, but not to score runs.

Timed Out:
If a new batsman takes longer than two minutes, from the time the previous wicket falls, to appear on the field.

These methods of getting out are listed in approximate order of how commonly they occur. The first five are reasonably common, the last five quite rare. The last three methods are almost never invoked.

Ards currently has two senior teams playing in the Northern Cricket Union - the 1st XI in the Senior League Section 3 and the 2nd XI in Junior 6. 1st XI matches are normally 40 overs and 2nd XI a maximum of 35. Matches are played on Saturdays and Sundays and players may play on either or both days depending on selection. There are also, from time to time, T20 matches. The season lasts from the last week in April until mid-September. Senior practices are held on Monday and Thursday evenings from 6.30-8.30pm at Londonderry Park. Individual coaching is available by arrangement with the coaches in the brand new net facility.

There are currently four Junior teams: the under 11, under 13 and under 15 levels play in the Northern Cricket Union leagues and cup competitions, and an U17 team plays in the Colts Cup only. Their games are mainly played in the evenings between May and August amd are normally T20 format. Practice sessions are held on Tuesday evening for the U15s from 6.45-8.30pm and Wednesday evening 6.45-8.30pm for U11 and U13, all at Londonderry Park. All boys and girls are welcome, irrespective of ability, and beginners to cricket will be assisted in learning the game.

During the off-season, indoor practice sessions are held in the Ards Leisure Centre during March and April. Details of these sessions, and general club news, are published on the Club's website and in the Newtownards Chronicle Cricket News section.

Ards CC now have, courtesy of the Council's investment in Londonderry Park:

  1. a new 9 pitch clay-based square which has already produced some excellent pitches with pace and bounce.
  2. two astro pitches on either end of the square for practice and match play.
  3. a huge catch fence on the Portaferry Road side of the ground.
  4. a new equipment store and scoring building.
  5. two 30m nets which are completely enclosed and safe. With such excellent facilities at Ards' disposal let's make sure that they are used each night of the week.

Further information may be obtained by contacting the Club's Honorary Secretary Rab Dunn or, for Junior cricket, Les Jones and Ronnie Balfour.
